### 1. One-Line Summary
* Dignics 05 is a high-performance, high-grip, high-ceiling rubber that rewards strong technique and quality impact; Rozena is the more forgiving “Tenergy-family” feel with easier control and stability.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * Dignics 05: Needs a bit more positive engagement to fully “wake up,” but still produces a solid, predictable ball once you commit.
        * Rozena: Easier free speed and depth on compact strokes; noticeably simpler in medium pace rallying.
    * **Top End:**
        * Dignics 05: Clearly higher ceiling—more pace and heavier ball when you accelerate and brush-drive hard.
        * Rozena: Good top speed, but caps out earlier; less “second gear” explosiveness from deep distance.
    * **Linearity:**
        * Dignics 05: More performance jump with impact—can feel bouncier when you cross a certain threshold.
        * Rozena: More linear and steady across impacts; easier to keep the same length under pressure.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * Dignics 05: Strong bite on the first loop, especially with good timing; excels when you load the ball.
        * Rozena: Very friendly opener—less punishing on imperfect contact; easier to clear the net with safe spin.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * Dignics 05: Higher peak spin and heavier rotation, especially on power loops and counterloops.
        * Rozena: High spin for its class, but lower peak; the ball is “spinnier” than many tensors, yet not at Dignics ceiling.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * Dignics 05: Stronger, more premium grip sensation and confidence on brushing contact.
        * Rozena: Grippy and consistent, but a step down in “bite” and micro-grab on extreme brushing.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * Dignics 05: Medium-high arc with strong kick; arc becomes more pronounced when you brush hard.
        * Rozena: Medium-high arc that feels smoother and less sharp; easier to place with compact form.
    * **Safety:**
        * Dignics 05: High safety when you use proper spin mechanics; demands better timing to avoid long/over.
        * Rozena: Very safe in real match situations—more margin for error on blocks, pushes, and rushed loops.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * Dignics 05: Crisper, more direct “pro” feedback; you feel the contact quality clearly.
        * Rozena: Softer and more muted; easier on the arm and more comfortable over long sessions.
    * **Dwell:**
        * Dignics 05: Good dwell at strong engagement; rewards clean brushing and acceleration.
        * Rozena: Feels like longer dwell at low-medium impact due to softness; helps lift backspin without perfect form.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * Dignics 05: More reactive to incoming spin and to your own touch errors; requires cleaner hands.
        * Rozena: Less sensitive and more stable; easier to keep pushes short and receives calmer.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * Dignics 05: Excellent once mastered, but demands disciplined wrist and angle control.
        * Rozena: Noticeably simpler for serve receive, drop shots, and flick setups; more “plug-and-play.”

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * Dignics 05: Can be bouncy if your angle is late; very effective with correct technique.
        * Rozena: One of its strengths—stable and predictable passive blocks with good placement.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * Dignics 05: Stronger counterloop/counterdrive power and spin—more bite through the ball.
        * Rozena: Very consistent countering at the table; less penetrating when both players add power.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Dignics 05 if:**
    * You generate your own pace and want a higher ceiling for power looping and counterlooping.
    * You prioritize maximum spin, heavy ball, and crisp feedback over forgiveness.
    * You play mid-distance or transition often from open-up to counter and finishing shots.
    * You’re comfortable managing higher sensitivity in receive and short game.

* **Choose Rozena if:**
    * You want an easier all-round rubber with strong control, especially in serve receive and blocks.
    * You value linearity, stability, and match consistency over peak performance.
    * Your strokes are compact or you’re developing technique and want “Tenergy-like” feel with more margin.
    * You prefer a slightly softer, more comfortable impact for long training and lower error rate.